<section xml:id="section-eigen-values-vectors-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p>
The following definitions are relative to a given <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>A</m>.
<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
	<title>eigenvector</title>
	<idx><h>eigenvector</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>eigenvector</h></idx>
	<p>	a nonzero vector <m>\uvec{x}</m> in <m>\R^n</m> such that <m>A\uvec{x}</m> is a scalar multiple of <m>\uvec{x}</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>eigenvalue</title>
	<idx><h>eigenvalue</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>eigenvalue</h></idx>
	<p> a scalar for which there exists an eigenvector <m>\uvec{x}</m> of <m>A</m> with <m>A\uvec{x}=\lambda\uvec{x}</m> </p>
	</li>

</dl>
</p>

<note><p>
	Eigenvectors and eigenvalues go together in pairs,
	with the connection between the two provided by the equality
	<m>A\uvec{x}=\lambda\uvec{x}</m>.
	In this situation, we say that the two objects <term>correspond</term> to each other.
	So we might say that <m>\uvec{x}</m> is an eigenvector of <m>A</m> that <term>corresponds</term> to the eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m>.
	Equivalently, we might say that <m>\lambda</m> is an eigenvalue of <m>A</m> that <term>corresponds</term> to the eigenvector <m>\uvec{x}</m>.
	However, note that an eigenvalue can correspond to many eigenvectors
	(in fact, an infinite number of them),
	an eigenvector must correspond to exactly one eigenvalue.
</p></note>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
	<title>eigenspace</title>
	<idx><h>eigenspace</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>eigenspace</h></idx>
	<p>
		the subspace of <m>\R^n</m> consisting of all eigenvectors of <m>A</m> that correspond to a specific eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m>,
		along with the zero vector
	</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><m>E_\lambda(A)</m></title>
	<p> notation for the eigenspace of matrix <m>A</m> corresponding to the eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<note><p>
In other resources you may seem the terms
<term>characteristic vector</term><idx><h>characteristic</h><h>vector</h></idx>,
<term>characteristic value</term><idx><h>characteristic</h><h>value</h></idx>,
and
<term>characteristic space</term><idx><h>characteristic</h><h>space</h></idx>
used in place of the terminology introduced above.
</p></note>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
	<title>characteristic polynomial</title>
	<idx><h>characteristic</h><h>polynomial (for a matrix)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>characteristic polynomial</h></idx>
	<p> the degree-<m>n</m> polynomial in the variable <m>\lambda</m> obtained by computing <m>\det(\lambda I - A)</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><m>c_A(\lambda)</m></title>
	<p> notation for the characteristic polynomial of matrix <m>A</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>characteristic equation</title>
	<idx><h>characteristic</h><h>equation (for a matrix)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>characteristic equation</h></idx>
	<p> the polynomial equation <m>\det(\lambda I - A) = 0</m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
